<br>
You guys and your love affair with &quot;Ole' Bang Bang.&quot;  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I have posted a proposal for a closed cycle NTR similar in size to a SaturnV which could place 1000 tons in orbit per launch.  There were some pretty good technical objections raised, but I think I have chewed through them all, and will be posting all that data in the NTR thread soon.<br>
<br>
That said: I think a Nuclear Lightbulb powered SSTO fully reusable launcher is perfectly feasible.  <br>
<br>
The ICANN design uses antimatter to trigger fuel spheres.  The beauty of the ICANN design is the very high fusion fraction of the pulse units.<br>
<br>
In general, seen in terms of fallout, fusion is far &quot;cleaner&quot; than fission.  Without using truly exotic materials, it is very difficult to get the critical mass of plutonium below 5 kilos or so.  (I may be off a bit on that.)  5 kilos of plutonium, if burned efficiently, yields WAY more than a kiloton.  Smaller yields than a kiloton were achieved by running the bomb in a very inefficient manner.<br>
<br>
The fuel pellets of an ICANN type device use very little U238 ( a few grams) and a much larger amount of tritium deuteride as the main source.  You get much more BANG per gram of fuel that way.<br>
<br>
Also, the fuel pellets are much smaller, the yield I have seen quoted translates to about 75 tons per pellet.  This means the whole design can scale smaller with efficiency than the Orion could.<br>
<br>
The ICANN design was supposed to have an Isp of 13,500, and the thrust shell (pusher plate to you Orion types) was a mere 350 tons or so.<br>
<br>
So, the NTR booster could place an entire ICANN type ship in orbit with one launch.  Whee!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Technology marches on, gentlemen.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=nebobgrenville>nebobgrenville</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://my.oregonstate.edu/courses/1/NE_114_X001_F2002/uploads/homepage/_1060577_1/triga.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 142<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(11/16/02 5:35:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=183.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Why havn't we built the Orion?</span><hr size=1> ICAN is still a form of External Pulsed Plasma Propulsion, in many ways it is simply a fusion Orion. I would love to see it work, but the technicle problems are not small: ICAN is not as simple as it sounds. First you have to hit a moving target through a debree cloud from multiple directions with ion beams at the same moment. If one hits befor the others, the pellet is knocked off course. This has been one of the great problems with Inertial Confinement Fusion in general. Then there is the antiproton storage problem. Storing then for years will take a leap in technology, and there is always the risk of storage failing and your fuel dissipearing. A fission Orion of comparible dry mass (350 ton propulsion unit) could produce over 100 times the trust of ICAN with 30% of its Isp using the origonal numbers(predicted improvements to the pulse units we have already developed since then could make it 200 times the thrust and 40% the Isp), all with more storible and reliable propellant. I still like the low propellant mass required for ICAN, though. Both have their advanteges and disadvanteges, but ICAN may not be viable to begin development for 20 years, fission EPPP is availible now. Fusion is the future, but we're not there yet.<br>
