<br>
True, true, but it seems far more sophisticated, especially in the way it generated power from fuel pellets and then couples that power to the spacecraft.  Note the sky-high Isp it achieves.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> First you have to hit a moving target through a debree cloud from multiple directions with ion beams at the same moment. If one hits befor the others, the pellet is knocked off course. This has been one of the great problems with Inertial Confinement Fusion in general. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, I personally don't like the whole ion confinement thing either.  I suspect the reason they do that is to make neutron capture easier for the fission stage of pellet ignition, but I have a few thoughts of my own on that topic.<br>
<br>
There is also a 200 gram lead shell around the fuel pellet that serves to &quot;cool down&quot; the energy coming out of the reaction, so it properly vaporizes the thrust shell.  Well, I would rip off those stupid ion beams and their related power systems and dump that hundred tons of mass into explosive lenses around each fuel pellet to do the compression the old fashioned way.  The lead shell could be changed into a hearty lump of Plumbitol lead-based explosive.  At the energy level those pellets release, all that matters is the lead ions are close by, any low-Z matter is simply transparent.<br>
<br>
Doing this also provides more mass to get tossed around, you'd get more thrust.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Then there is the antiproton storage problem. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Very true, but work is moving quickly on that front, and ICANN II is specifically designed to use tiny amounts of antimatter.  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> A fission Orion of comparible dry mass (350 ton propulsion unit) could produce over 100 times the trust of ICAN with 30% of its Isp using the origonal numbers(predicted improvements to the pulse units we have already developed since then could make it 200 times the thrust and 40% the Isp), all with more storible and reliable propellant. I still like the low propellant mass required for ICAN, though. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yeah, isn't Isp great?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   For a deep space mission, the ICANN II is purely better.  It has enough thrust to pile up DeltaV fast.  Plus, the higher Isp means more cargo for a given ship size.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> I wonder if the SiC thrust shell concept with lead propellant could be put to use with a fission EPPP? Would it be better? <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, the lead is not really propellant, it's just there to condition the output spectrum so the ablative thrust shell absorbs the energy more efficiency.  The &quot;propellant&quot; is the actual thrust shell, which has layers blown off and provides thrust that way.<br>
<br>
Here's a <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.pr-llc.com/prop/ICAN.pdf"> link </a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> to a moderately huge .pdf with lots and lots of data about the way ICANN II is supposed to work.  <br>
<br>
I see no reason why a fission Orion couldn't use the same principals.  Would be interesting to see the numbers on it!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
